<div id="review_37604505" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/37604505" />
    <a title="Daniel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/638550-daniel"><img alt="Daniel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1399866937p2/638550.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/37604505?book_show_action=true">Nov 13, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Daniel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Daniel" href="/user/show/638550-daniel">Daniel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/638550-daniel?shelf=plays">plays</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/638550-daniel?shelf=theatre">theatre</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer37604505" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5834448430277220465">As a former reader of plays submitted to a nationally recognized theatre, I remember reading this play well before it was ever staged. I didn&apos;t care for it a whole lot at the time, but I suspect it has gone through a few rewrites to get where it is today.<br/><br/>What I liked, now, about this script is the very theatricality of it. Kushner understands theatre and writes to it exceedingly well.<br/><br/>The characters are well defined and the &apos;forwards,&apos; the moments in the play which keep the reader/audience wantin</span>
  <span id="freeText5834448430277220465" style="display:none">As a former reader of plays submitted to a nationally recognized theatre, I remember reading this play well before it was ever staged. I didn't care for it a whole lot at the time, but I suspect it has gone through a few rewrites to get where it is today.<br /><br />What I liked, now, about this script is the very theatricality of it. Kushner understands theatre and writes to it exceedingly well.<br /><br />The characters are well defined and the 'forwards,' the moments in the play which keep the reader/audience wanting to know what happens next, are strong.<br /><br />What I still don't care for (and what would have made this very wrong for the theatre for which I read this originally)is the graphic language and imagery. <br /><br />I've never considered myself prudish. I think the short works of Steve Almond are great, and they are often sexually graphic. I enjoy the works of David Mamet, and his language is incredibly foul. My own works run the gamut of gore, sexually graphic, sexual innuendo, and foul-mouthed, so I don't think that's my problem here.<br /><br />But I fully admit that it might be the homosexual nature of all this. But still, I think it's more than that.<br /><br />First, I don't think I cared to hear about (more than once), and see, a character, dying of AIDS, "shitting blood." If it was there to touch a nerve,it worked -- the first time. Even in this short play, I became deadened to it and was simply disgusted.<br /><br />And the sexual references, nearly all homosexual sex, made me uneasy. I think, I really think, that it had less to do with the gay nature of the sex but was because I never felt that any of the sex was the result of caring, loving relationships. Even the one heterosexual reference (the wife offering to perform fellatio on her husband), seemed 'dirty' because it was apparant that they didn't really have a love for each other.<br /><br />When a script such as this is this full of sex, and yet the characters don't appear to be emotionally involved with one another, the sex is cheapened and seems very self indulgent. And then I don't care about these selfish characters.<br /><br />Some will argue that the relationship between Prior and Louis was loving -- having lasted four years, but I don't get that. I never see that. It seems ... it feels ... demanding. Almost as though it was forced on at least one of them. <br /><br />Theatrical. Intelligent. Well-defined characters. But not a single character yet that I find embraceable.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5834448430277220465" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

